<DOC><DOCNO> AP890203-0108 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 1308EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BoatPeople     02-03 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Boat People,0189</SECOND><HEAD>Vietnamese to Visit Hong Kong to Process Refugees</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vietnamese officials will come to Hong Kong thismonth to try to arrange this British colony's first majorrepatriation of Vietnamese boat people, a government spokesman saidFriday.   The four-member Vietnamese delegation will leave for Bangkok,Thailand, on Feb. 10, and fly on to Hong Kong, said governmentspokesman Akber Khan.   They will issue travel documents to countrymen who wish to returnhome after fleeing Vietnam by boat. About 300 have asked to go home,and Hanoi has cleared 141 cases for consideration, officials say.   More than 25,000 Vietnamese are detained in Hong Kong camps,including about 15,000 eligible to resettle but not accepted by aforeign government.   About 10,000 arrived after a new policy took effect in June.Under the new rules, they face forced repatriation unless they canprove they fled their homeland for fear of persecution.   Until now, only about two dozen of the Vietnamese who sailed toHong Kong since the end of the Vietnam War have voluntarily returnedto their homeland.</TEXT></DOC>